title Auto-supersede on overwrite
edge explains commit:f56fa8b0bd2ff16dffb0bb2369dc66a6c868226f

Discovered by dogfooding: I accidentally overwrote the 'Enforcement
via hooks' decision note with a 'Session complete' context note on the
same commit. The old note was lost from the notes ref (recoverable only
via reflog). Fix: before git notes add -f, capture the existing note's
blob OID and inject it as a supersedes header. Now the chain is always
preserved. Old blobs stay in git's object store and are retrievable
via git cat-file -p <supersedes-oid>.
